SIMPLE: incidence
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incidence
<hw>In"ci*dence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>incidence</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A falling on or upon; an incident; an event; an
occurrence.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>The direction in which a body,
or a ray of light or heat, falls on any surface.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In equal <qex>incidences</qex> there is a considerable inequality
of refractions.</q> <rj><qau>Sir I. Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The rate or ratio at which something occurs; <as>as,
the <ex>incidence</ex> of murder in Los Angeles; the <ex>incidence</ex>
of cancer in men over 50</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Angle of incidence</b></col>, <cd>the angle which a ray
of light, or the line of incidence of a body, falling on any surface,
makes with a perpendicular to that surface; also formerly, the
complement of this angle.</cd> -- <col><b>Line of incidence</b></col>,
<cd>the line in the direction of which a surface is struck by a body,
ray of light, and the like.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incidency</ent>⟦br⟧
